example.correct_output:
{
  "voice_dna": {
    "signature_vocabulary": ["collision", "friction", "promiscuous attention", "cross-domain", "accumulation"],
    "sentence_pattern": "Short declarative provocation followed by compound explanatory sentences with em-dash pivots; argumentative sections close with a compressed one-liner that functions as an aphorism",
    "rhetorical_devices": [
      "contrast: 'Not slightly wrong — fundamentally, structurally wrong'",
      "analogy: 'less a lightning bolt and more a slow accumulation — a pressure building behind a wall you did not know you were building, until it breaks'",
      "enumeration: 'The architect reading neuroscience. The novelist studying supply chain logistics. The composer who could explain the history of Ottoman military strategy.'"
    ],
    "tone": "Contrarian and provocative as primary mode, with analytical rigor as counterweight; dismisses romantic myths directly and without hedging",
    "exemplar_quotes": [
      "Most advice about creativity is wrong. Not slightly wrong — fundamentally, structurally wrong — because it focuses on the output when the problem lives entirely in the input.",
      "Creativity happens in the collision between what you have absorbed and what you refuse to accept.",
      "Cross-domain collision is not a technique. It is a posture."
    ]
  },
  "chapter_observations": "This chapter opens with a blunt inversion of received wisdom, establishing a contrarian voice immediately. More combative than analytical chapters elsewhere — shorter declarative bursts, direct dismissals ('a word I find nearly useless'), and the closing aphorism is characteristic of how the author ends argumentative sections: a compressed thesis with slogan-like finality."
}

